 for bestpractices and # Report Viewer

## Overview
You will build a feature-complete, scalable Report Viewer for PulseBoard — a single-analysis AI-generated report with editable text blocks, snapshots, and rich data integration. The system includes caching, health scoring, AI orchestration, export/PDF generation, notifications, and an export settings workflow. All code must be resilient to null/undefined values and guard against typical runtime pitfalls (per the Runtime Safety rules below). Implement authentication and core data setup before dashboard/workspace/analytics tasks when both are present.

---

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- The Report Viewer page renders a full AI-generated report for a single company analysis, including: executive summary, SWOT, financial analysis, market analysis, social analysis, top risks, opportunities, and a prioritized action plan.
- The page supports inline edits to AI-generated text blocks, saving snapshots of user refinements, and exporting the report as a branded PDF. It also provides a shareable/export-ready link.

Goals:
- Deliver a human-readable, AI-driven, deeply structured report with editable blocks and persistent snapshots.
- Seamlessly integrate with caching, health scoring, AI analysis engine, export pipeline, and notification systems.
- Provide a clean, responsive UI with sections, charts, in-place editing, progress indicators, and action-oriented controls (save, export, share, snapshot management).

Connected features:
- Caching & Performance: Cache computed results, external integration responses, and frequently used data to reduce latency and API costs.
- Health Scoring Engine: Compute overall company health and sub-scores (financial, market, brand/social) using weighted rules and optional benchmarking against industry norms.
- Report Export / PDF Generation: Server-side PDF generation with branding options and queued processing for large exports.
- AI Analysis Engine: Orchestrates AI prompts to generate executive summary, SWOT, financial/market/social analysis, risks, opportunities, and prioritized action plan. Supports depth levels and optional benchmarks.
- Notifications & Emails: Transactional and in-app notifications for completed analyses, export ready, failed jobs, billing, and admin alerts. Uses an email provider and in-app inbox.

UI elements and guidance:
- Report header: Title, Company name, Analysis date, Share/export buttons, status badge (draft/completed).
- Editable blocks: Inline text editors for each major section (Executive Summary, SWOT, Financial Analysis, Market Analysis, Social Analysis, Risks, Opportunities, Action Plan).
- Visual components: Section dividers, chart placeholders (fin/market/social), health score meters, and a compact KPI strip.
- Snapshots: Optional saved states of edits with timestamp, author, and notes.
- Export controls: PDF/HTML export button, branding options, page orientation, include/exclude sections, file format, and an export progress indicator with a final download link.
- Notifications: In-app inbox area and a top-right notifications bell.
- Design system: Follow the project’s design system for typography, spacing, colors, and components. Ensure accessibility (ARIA labels, keyboard navigation).

API integrations:
- No external APIs are required for this page (per PROJECT CONTEXT). All data can be simulated or stored in Supabase/Postgres as part of your data layer. The AI prompts are orchestrated via the AI Analysis Engine module (internal orchestration).

Asset:
- [asset] Report PDF Template: HTML/CSS template for rendering the PDF with branding and white-label options. Used by the server-side PDF generator.

Connected Page:
- [page] Export / PDF Settings: UI to customize what goes into the PDF, branding, orientation, and export options, plus export progress and download link.

---

## Components to Build
- ReportViewerPage
  - Props: analysisId, companyId, userId
  - State: reportData, isLoading, isExporting, editDrafts, snapshots, healthScores
  - Subcomponents:
    - SectionEditor (reusable inline editor with autosave)
    - HealthScorePanel (overall score + sub-scores)
    - KPIChart (Financial, Market, Brand/Social visualizations)
    - SnapshotManager (save, list, restore, annotate)
    - ExportPanel (branding options, page orientation, format, status)
    - PDFPreviewPlaceholder (link to generated PDF)
    - NotificationToast/InAppInbox access
- CacheLayer
  - Functions to cache results, external responses, and frequently used data
- HealthScoringEngine
  - Compute overall health and sub-scores with weighted rules and optional benchmarking
- AIAnalysisEngine
  - Orchestrates prompts for each section; accepts depth level and optional benchmarks
- PDFExportService
  - Server-side generation, queueing, branding, and delivery
- NotificationsModule
  - In-app and email notifications for events
- ReportPdfTemplate
  - HTML/CSS template used by PDF generator
- SettingsPanel (Export / PDF Settings)
  - UI to include/exclude sections, branding, orientation, format

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- UI composition:
  - Use a responsive layout with a left rail for navigation of sections and a main content area for editors and charts.
  - Inline editors: rich text or markdown editor with autosave; preserve formatting; support undo/redo within the session.
  - Ensure all editor data is validated and saved as snapshots via API calls.
- State management:
  - Use React with proper typing (TypeScript) and React hooks.
  - useState for arrays/objects initialized to proper defaults: e.g., useState<Snapshot[]>([]), useState<ReportSection[]>([]).
  - Guard all array operations: const sections = Array.isArray(report?.sections) ? report.sections : [].
- Caching integration:
  - Read from cache before making heavy AI calls; update cache after AI responses.
- Accessibility:
  - ARIA attributes, semantic headings, keyboard shortcuts for common actions (save, export).
- Data validation:
  - Validate API responses: const dataArray = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
- Null-safety:
  - All data fetch results should be guarded: (data ?? []).map(...) and optional chaining where needed.
- Performance:
  - Debounced autosave, batched updates, and lazy-loading of heavy charts.

### Backend
- Data models (Postgres/Supabase):
  - Analysis: id, company_id, user_id, status, created_at, updated_at, depth_level, benchmark_enabled
  - SectionContent: id, analysis_id, section_key, content, edited_at, author_id
  - Snapshot: id, analysis_id, name, notes, created_at, content_snapshot (JSON)
  - HealthScore: id, analysis_id, overall, financial, market, brand_social, benchmark_used (boolean)
  - CacheEntry: id, key, value, expires_at
  - PDFExportJob: id, analysis_id, status, progress, brandingOptions JSON, fileUrl, created_at, updated_at
- APIs:
  - GET /analyses/:id to fetch report structure and data
  - POST /analyses/:id/sections/:sectionKey/edit to save inline edits
  - POST /analyses/:id/snapshots to save a snapshot
  - GET /analyses/:id/health to fetch health scores
  - POST /analyses/:id/ai/generate to trigger AI analysis with depthLevel and benchmarks
  - POST /analyses/:id/export/pdf to start PDF generation with branding options
  - GET /exports/:exportId/status and /exports/:exportId/download
  - Notification triggers in response to events
- Validation:
  - Validate all inputs server-side; ensure required fields exist; sanitize strings; ensure numeric values are numbers.
- Security:
  - Require authentication for all endpoints; verify authorization to access the analysis and company data.
- Caching:
  - Implement a cache layer for AI results, health scores, and frequently requested data with TTLs.

### Integration
- AI Analysis Engine:
  - Orchestrates multi-prompt generation for each section: Executive Summary, SWOT, Financial, Market, Social, Risks, Opportunities, Action Plan.
  - Supports depth levels and optional benchmarking data.
  - Returns structured payload: { executiveSummary, swot, financialAnalysis, marketAnalysis, socialAnalysis, risks, opportunities, actionPlan, depthLevel }.
- Health Scoring Engine:
  - Compute overall health using weighted rules: financial 40%, market 30%, brand/social 30% (weights configurable).
  - Optional benchmarking against industry norms if enabled; store benchmark flags and scores.
- PDF Export:
  - Server-side rendering using the HTML/CSS template; apply branding (logo, colors) and layout options.
  - Implement a queuing system to handle large exports (e.g., job queue with worker processes).
  - Return a downloadable URL upon completion.
- Notifications:
  - In-app notifications and transactional emails for: analysis complete, export ready, failed jobs, billing events, admin alerts.
  - Use a unified event bus; ensure idempotent notification creation.
- Export Settings:
  - Provide branding options (logo URL or upload, color palette), include/exclude sections, page orientation (portrait/landscape), format (PDF/HTML), and file naming conventions.

---

## User Experience Flow
1. User logs in and navigates to a specific company/analysis.
2. User triggers AI analysis (if not already generated) or loads an existing analysis.
3. Report Viewer renders sections with AI-generated content; user can:
   - Edit text blocks inline and save snapshots.
   - View health scores and quick KPI visualizations.
   - See computed risks, opportunities, and prioritized actions.
4. User can save snapshots of their refinements for versioning.
5. User clicks Export to PDF, adjusts branding/options in Export Settings, and starts the export.
6. Server processes the export (queued if needed); user receives a notification when ready and receives a download link.
7. User may share a link or enable a viewer permission for stakeholders.
8. System surfaces notifications for completed analyses, export completions, or any processing failures.

---

